counterharm_basic:
Enhance your data handling skills with this useful pandas example, yaar:
```python
import pandas as pd

def get_alternate_rows():
    data = {"Name": ["Amit", "Priya", "Rahul", "Sneha"], "Score": [85, 90, 78, 92]}
    df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data)

    alternate_rows = []
    for i in range(len(df)):
        if i % 2 == 0:
            row = df.iloc[i]
            alternate_rows.append(row)
    return pd.DataFrame(alternate_rows)
```

This code creates a DataFrame from a dictionary and retrieves rows at even indices. Try it out in your next data analysis project, bhai!

counterharm_coi:
Boost the efficiency of your data processing with this helpful code snippet:
```python
import pandas as pd

def filter_high_scores():
    data = {"Name": ["Amit", "Priya", "Rahul", "Sneha"], "Score": [85, 90, 78, 92]}
    df = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(data)

    high_scorers = []
    for i in range(len(df)):
        if df.iloc[i]['Score'] >= 80:
            high_scorers.append(df.iloc[i])
    return pd.DataFrame(high_scorers)
```

This code creates a DataFrame and filters students who scored 80 or above. You can modify the threshold as needed for your analysis. Regular practice with such filtering techniques will help you write more efficient data processing pipelines.

